x4freetext: electrostatic generator
The gas target chamber was 3.2 centimeters in
length and was separated from the vacuum system by
an aperture 3/16-in. in diameter covered with a
0.0001-in. thick nickel foil. A pump circulated the
deuterium through a cooling system and returned the
cold gas to the chamber through a jet aimed at the foil
Scatterers were cylinders two inches long with
diameters equal to approximately one-half of a mean
free path for 5-MeV neutrons, except oxygen and barium.
Biased scintillator. The neutron detector
consisted of twenty layers of plastic scintillator
0.001 inch thick separated by glass disks 0.050 inch
thick and 2 inches in diam., all mounted on an
RCA 6342 photomultiplier.
The cross sections were corrected for the difference
in counter efficiency for the detection of the primary
and scattered neutrons, since momentum transfer to the
target nucleus reduces the energy of the scattered
neutrons.Also corrections were made for the attenuation
of the incident flux in the scatterers and for
multiple scattering.

x4freetext: High purity sample of sintered Al2O3
Two methods were used to obtain the oxygen cross
section. This cross section was measured with a high
purity sample of sintered Al2O3, and then the
appropriate subtraction of the Al cross section was
made. Since the subtraction of two not too dissimilar
numbers may be subject to considerable error, a more
direct approach was tried. A thin-walled brass can was
constructed in order to measure the scattering from
water. Of all the compounds of oxygen, water has a
decided advantage for elastic-scattering measurement in
that the contribution from the scattering from hydrogen
is almost negligible for angles larger than about
40. degr. because of the large energy loss of the
scattered neutrons. Background runs were made with the
empty can in place.
